    <main class="planet-detail" data-planet="mars">
        <div class="hero-section">
            <img src="../images/mars.jpg" alt="Mars" class="hero-image">
            <div class="hero-info">
                <h2>The Red Planet</h2>
                <p class="hero-description">Mars is the fourth planet from the Sun and the second-smallest planet in the Solar System. Known as the Red Planet due to iron oxide on its surface, it's the most explored planet beyond Earth.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="content-grid">
            <section class="info-card">
                <h3>Basic Facts</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Type:</strong> Terrestrial Planet</li>
                    <li><strong>Distance from Sun:</strong> 227.9 million km</li>
                    <li><strong>Diameter:</strong> 6,792 km (0.53 Ã— Earth)</li>
                    <li><strong>Mass:</strong> 6.39 Ã— 10Â²Â³ kg (0.107 Ã— Earth)</li>
                    <li><strong>Surface Temperature:</strong> -140Â°C to 20Â°C</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital Period:</strong> 687 Earth days</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="info-card">
                <h3>Atmosphere & Climate</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Atmosphere:</strong> Carbon dioxide (95%)</li>
                    <li><strong>Surface Pressure:</strong> 0.006 atm (1% of Earth)</li>
                    <li><strong>Dust Storms:</strong> Global storms possible</li>
                    <li><strong>Polar Ice Caps:</strong> Water and COâ‚‚ ice</li>
                    <li><strong>Wind Speed:</strong> Up to 110 km/h</li>
                    <li><strong>Seasonal Changes:</strong> Similar to Earth</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="info-card">
                <h3>Surface Features</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Olympus Mons:</strong> Largest volcano (21.9 km)</li>
                    <li><strong>Valles Marineris:</strong> Canyon system (4,000 km)</li>
                    <li><strong>Tharsis Bulge:</strong> Volcanic plateau</li>
                    <li><strong>Impact Craters:</strong> Heavily cratered surface</li>
                    <li><strong>Sand Dunes:</strong> Extensive dune fields</li>
                    <li><strong>Ancient Riverbeds:</strong> Evidence of water</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="info-card">
                <h3>Moons & Satellites</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Phobos:</strong> Larger moon (22.2 km)</li>
                    <li><strong>Deimos:</strong> Smaller moon (12.6 km)</li>
                    <li><strong>Origin:</strong> Captured asteroids</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital Period:</strong> 7.7 and 30.3 hours</li>
                    <li><strong>Future:</strong> Phobos will crash into Mars</li>
                    <li><strong>Exploration:</strong> Potential human base</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="info-card">
                <h3>Exploration History</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Mariner 4:</strong> First flyby (1965)</li>
                    <li><strong>Viking Program:</strong> First landers (1976)</li>
                    <li><strong>Pathfinder:</strong> Sojourner rover (1997)</li>
                    <li><strong>Spirit & Opportunity:</strong> Rovers (2004-2019)</li>
                    <li><strong>Curiosity:</strong> Active rover (2012-)</li>
                    <li><strong>Perseverance:</strong> Latest rover (2021-)</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="info-card">
                <h3>Future Human Missions</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>SpaceX Starship:</strong> Planned missions</li>
                    <li><strong>NASA Artemis:</strong> Moon to Mars program</li>
                    <li><strong>Habitat Design:</strong> Underground shelters</li>
                    <li><strong>Resource Utilization:</strong> ISRU technology</li>
                    <li><strong>Radiation Protection:</strong> Shielding required</li>
                    <li><strong>Life Support:</strong> Closed-loop systems</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
        </div>

        <section class="fun-facts">
            <h3>Fun Facts</h3>
            <div class="facts-grid">
                <div class="fact">
                    <h4>ğŸ—» Tallest Mountain</h4>
                    <p>Olympus Mons on Mars is the tallest mountain in the solar system, three times higher than Mount Everest.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact">
                    <h4>ğŸŒŠ Ancient Oceans</h4>
                    <p>Mars once had liquid water on its surface, with evidence of ancient riverbeds and lake beds.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact">
                    <h4>ğŸŒªï¸ Dust Devils</h4>
                    <p>Mars has frequent dust devils that can reach heights of 8 kilometers and last for hours.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact">
                    <h4>ğŸ”´ Rusty Surface</h4>
                    <p>Mars appears red because its surface is covered in iron oxide (rust), giving it the nickname "Red Planet."</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>

